The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | NYSE to acquire 5% of MCX
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       NYSE to acquire 5% of MCX
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	New Delhi, May 2: The government today cleared a proposal by NYSE Euronext, the parent company of the New York Stock Exchange, to buy a 5 per cent stake in the Multi Commodity Exchange (MCX)  Indias largest commodity trading platform  from Financial Technologies (FTIL) for Rs 218.51 crore. MCX is part of Financial Technologies.        
	In February 2008, the NYSE signed a deal with the MCX at an enterprise value of Rs 4,400 crore. The stake sale process, which is likely to be completed by June-end, will decrease FTILs shareholding to about 32 per cent, while the total foreign direct investment (FDI) in the MCX would go up to 22 per cent.         
	Finance minister P. Chidambaram has approved 14 other foreign direct investment (FDI) proposals worth Rs 309 crore. Images Multimedia, a portal for retail and other business information, plan to buy a 26 per cent share in speciality magazines for Rs 33.37 crore.        
	Metal One Corporation, a Japan-based steel product supplier, which plans to invest Rs 32 crore to set up a wholly owned subsidiary has received a go-ahead.         
	Another Japanese firm, Sumitomo Heavy Industrys plan to invest Rs 1 crore to set up a wholly owned subsidiary in India was also approved.        
	TRW Aftermarket Asia of Singapore will bring in FDI worth Rs 21.20 crore to set up a manufacturing base for automobile components.                                                                                                                                      
